    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1876-05-20T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1876-05-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="139" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d139">
                <head>No. 129.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Fish</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Hoffman</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1876-05-20">
                            <hi rend="italic">May</hi> 20,
                                1876</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Hoffman</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Chargé, London:</hi>
                </p>
                <p>Lord Derby’s note not received until 17th instant. Public journals report
                            the attorney-general as having said, on 13th, on asking Winslow to be
                            remanded for ten days, that unless reply were received within that time,
                            no further detention would be asked. Lord Derby’s note cannot be replied
                            to by telegraph; no other mode of transmission could put it in London by
                            the 23d.</p>
                <p>If the British government is determined to refuse to surrender the
                            fugitive, except on receiving the stipulation demanded, it is right to
                            say to Lord Derby that it is impossible to give the stipulation. The
                            President has not the power, if he were disposed to do so, as will be
                            explained in a reply to his note, now being prepared, and which will be
                            forwarded at an early day.</p>
                <p>You will read this to Lord Derby.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>FISH,<lb/>
                        <hi rend="italic">Secretary</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
